# Publish-Ready User State

Assume this repository may be pushed to GitHub at any time.

- Do not add or keep user-specific, machine-specific, generated, secret, or one-person working files in tracked source.
- If a feature creates per-user state, store it in a user-local location on first boot, not in the repo. Prefer ignored local paths such as `.graph-agent/` or an OS/user-data directory.
- Only commit portable defaults, templates, fixtures, or sample data that are safe for every clone.
- When introducing a new local artifact, update `.gitignore` in the same change so it is ignored immediately.
- Prefer bootstrap flows like "copy from bundled default into ignored local storage on first run" instead of writing mutable state into `src/`, `tests/`, or other tracked project files.

Examples:

- Good: track `.env.example`, ignore `.env`.
- Good: ship bundled sample graphs, but persist edits in ignored user-local storage.
- Bad: commit personal config, machine paths, local caches, runtime exports, or mutable user documents.
